<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>SSL International<Node id="17"/>, which is being investigated by the <Node id="54"/>Serious Fraud Office<Node id="74"/> for overstating its results, is to replace <Node id="118"/>Arthur Andersen<Node id="133"/>, the auditors under fire from some investors for failing to spot the irregularity.<Node id="216"/>

<Node id="218"/>The healthcare group, which makes Durex condoms and Scholl sandals, has put the audit contract up for tender.<Node id="327"/>

<Node id="329"/>Arthur Andersen<Node id="344"/> has not been invited to reapply and is not being considered.<Node id="405"/>

<Node id="407"/>It declined to comment on <Node id="433"/>Thursday<Node id="441"/>, but is expected to say it is departing by mutual agreement.<Node id="502"/>

<Node id="504"/>It is said to be expressing confidence privately that the <Node id="562"/>SFO<Node id="565"/> investigation will vindicate it.<Node id="598"/>

<Node id="600"/>SSL<Node id="603"/> said on <Node id="612"/>Thursday<Node id="620"/>: &quot;The process to appoint an auditor is well under way&quot; but declined to comment further.<Node id="708"/>

<Node id="710"/>People close to the company said <Node id="743"/>Andersen<Node id="751"/> had not put its name forward but even if it had it would have been extremely unlikely to have been selected.<Node id="860"/>

<Node id="862"/>Replacing the auditors will mark another important change at <Node id="923"/>SSL<Node id="926"/>, which over the <Node id="943"/>past year<Node id="952"/> has seen the departure of its finance director, chief executive, two other executive directors and the planned retirement of its chairman.<Node id="1091"/>

<Node id="1093"/>The auditors were attacked by private investors at <Node id="1144"/>last month<Node id="1154"/>&apos;s annual meeting for failing to detect that <Node id="1199"/>SSL<Node id="1202"/> had overstated sales by <Node id="1227"/>£22m<Node id="1232"/> (<Node id="1234"/>$31m<Node id="1238"/>) and profits before tax and exceptionals by <Node id="1283"/>£19m<Node id="1288"/> in the <Node id="1296"/>1999<Node id="1300"/> and <Node id="1305"/>2000 financial years<Node id="1325"/>.<Node id="1326"/>

<Node id="1328"/>About 100 investors voted against the board&apos;s proposal to retain <Node id="1393"/>Arthur Anderse<Node id="1407"/>n but were defeated by a large margin by institutional investors who backed the proposal.<Node id="1496"/>

<Node id="1498"/>However, <Node id="1507"/>Stuart Wallis<Node id="1520"/>, <Node id="1522"/>SSL<Node id="1525"/>&apos;s chairman, told the meeting that the company would put the audit contract, which was worth <Node id="1618"/>£700,000<Node id="1627"/> <Node id="1628"/>last year<Node id="1637"/>, up for tender.<Node id="1653"/>

<Node id="1655"/>The company said the overstatement appeared to have been caused by a complex fraud.<Node id="1738"/>

<Node id="1740"/>On <Node id="1743"/>Wednesday<Node id="1752"/>, the <Node id="1758"/>SFO<Node id="1761"/> launched an investigation into whether <Node id="1801"/>SSL<Node id="1804"/> employees or former employees might have committed criminal offences.<Node id="1874"/>

<Node id="1876"/>The <Node id="1880"/>SFO<Node id="1883"/> has studied the findings of an investigation by <Node id="1932"/>KPMG<Node id="1936"/>, the professional services firm, and <Node id="1974"/>DLA<Node id="1977"/>, a law firm, which were called in by <Node id="2015"/>Gary Watts<Node id="2025"/>, <Node id="2027"/>SSL<Node id="2030"/>&apos;s finance director.<Node id="2050"/>

<Node id="2052"/>The inquiry found the results were overstated through the use of fake invoices, goods that never reached customers, and inflated exceptional costs.<Node id="2199"/>
